## 7. Plain-chat models (Claude.ai web, ChatGPT web — no file access)

You can't use `@file` here since the model can't read your disk. Instead:

- Paste a file **once**, label it: `$F1 = <paste file>`.
- In later messages, refer to `$F1#fn:name` — the model already has the
  content in context, so it doesn't need a re-paste, just the pointer.
- Only re-paste a file if you've changed it *outside* the conversation (e.g.,
  edited locally) — and even then, paste only the changed function with
  `FMT:snippet` framing: `$F1#fn:movePiece updated: <snippet>`.

## 8. Making it persistent

- **Claude Code**: put the §1 block into a skill (see the companion
  `SKILL.md`) — Claude loads it automatically, you don't paste it each time.
- **Codex CLI / Codex with repos**: drop the §1 block into your repo's
  `AGENTS.md`. Codex reads that automatically as project instructions.
- **ChatGPT / Codex web**: paste §1 into "Custom Instructions" once — applies
  to all future chats.
- **Claude.ai web**: paste §1 as your first message in a chat, or save it as
  a personal "Style"/preset if you use one.

---

## 9. Caveats

- PCP shrinks *your* tokens, not the model's reasoning. For genuinely novel
  or ambiguous tasks, don't use `EXPL:0` — give the model the room it needs.
- 75% is realistic for **iterative coding sessions** (lots of repeated
  file/context). For one-shot questions with little reusable context, savings
  will be smaller (10–30%) — there's just less redundancy to remove.
- If a model ever seems to misread a tag, just spell it out that one time —
  PCP is a convention, not a guarantee, and clarity always wins over
  compression.
